	   <a name=96981958328560></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96981958328560><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>Learning Bonds of Force usage</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1037><span id= >Invectus</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>10 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Sep 24th 2:19 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>This is mainly for Wizards who have not reached level 29 yet, or who are more group-oriented and have not practiced BoF kiting yet.<br><br>As everyone knows, at level 29, we get the spell Bonds of Force. I didn't really learn to solo with this spell until level 31. Having found soloing to be very difficult in the 20s, I had given up trying in favor of grouping, but once we get BoF, soloing becomes a very viable option once more.<br><br>Pick a zone that you are already familiar with. Rather than dive into a zone full of high blues or yellows, I went back to good old South Karana. All of the following was WITHOUT the benefit of SoW.<br><br>I started by getting out around max. casting range, and casting it on a blue Aviak Harrier (I knew I could take this guy with standard root & shoot). I turned around and ran, counting slowly. When I got to a count of 12, I stopped and cast Inferno Shock. I was out of range, so I ran again and stopped at 10. This time I was in range and the frying commenced. By the 3rd hit, the bird was down. Next I tried the same thing with Avocets and Coursers, then a Charger. Practiced some more in Rathe Mts. (less room to run) on Giant Skels and blue Cyclops. By the end of all this practice, I felt confident enough to go try it out in Lake of Ill Omen (at the entrances to the goblin tunnels) and Frontier Mts.<br><br>Some Wizards who have the Staff of Temperate Flux use that as their range-judging device, but as I haven't gotten around to getting the last component for the quest yet, I find my counting method works pretty well.<br><br>Key things to keep in mind:<br><br>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;Keep Root loaded and hot keyed, if BoF fails, you can do one of 3 things: <br>a] root the pull(if it's a single), wait for it to wear off, and try again. Trying again is tricky, however. If the mob is fast enough, or you are too close when root wears off, you can end up BoF'ing yourself as well. <br>b]root it and revert to root & shoot<br>c]root it and gate<br><br>2) If you are out of range when you stop, run again. Don't try a second cast, most mobs will have caught up to you by then. You have plenty of time.<br><br>3) If you are using the counting method to judge range, you will find that different mobs require different counts, depending on their speed.<br><br>I know this post may sound obvious to all you high-level Wizzes out there, but I just wanted to pass along my own recent experience to our younger sisters and brothers who are moving into the larger world.<br><br>Also, not mentioned in any of this is the fact that at 34, we get Circle of Force, one of our best AoE spells, which opens the door to AE Kiting - a whole 'nother can o' worms:) <br><br>&nbsp;<br>Invectus Stormborn<br>57 Evoker<br>Leader of <br>A'dileab de Paegen<br>Tunare Server</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
